obj_root_law_sections_55_content:
  string
  line 55
  line `1 [5A. Apportionment of income between spouses governed by Portuguese Civil Code. — ( 1 )`
  line `Where the husband and wife are governed by the system of community of property (known under the`
  line `Portuguese Civil Code of 1860 as “COMMUNIAO DOS BENS”) in force in the State of Goa and in the`
  line `Union territories of Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu, the income of the husband and of the`
  line `wife under any head of income shall not be assessed as that of such community of property (whether`
  line `treated as an association of persons or a body of individuals), but such income of the husband and of the`
  line `wife under each head of income (other than under the head “Salaries”) shall be apport ioned equally`
  line `between the husband and the wife and the income so apportioned shall be included separately in the total`
  line `income of the husband and of the wife respectively, and the remaining provisions of this Act shall apply`
  line accordingly.
  line `( 2 ) Where the husband or, as the case may be, the wife governed by the aforesaid system of`
  line `community of property has any income under the head “Salaries”, such income shall be included in the`
  line `total income of the spouse who has actually earned it.]`
  line `6. Residence in India. — For the purposes of this Act, —`
  line `( 1 ) An individual is said to be resident in India in any previous year, if he —`
  line `( a ) is in India in that year for a period or periods amounting in all to one hundred and eighty-`
  line `two days or more; or`
  line `2 * * * * *`
  line `( c ) having within the four years preceding that year been in India for a period or periods`
  line `amounting in all to three hundred and sixty-five days or more, is in India for a period or periods`
  line `amounting in all to sixty days or more in that year.`
  line `3 [ Explanation 4 [1]. — In the case of an individual, —`
  line `( a ) being a citizen of India, who leaves India in any previous year 5 [as a member of the crew`
  line `of an Indian ship as defined in clause ( 18 ) of section 3 of the Merchant Shipping Act, 1958 (44 of`
  line `1958), or] for the purposes of employment outside India, the provisions of sub-clause ( c ) shall`
  line `apply in relation to that year as if for the words “sixty days”, occurring therein, the words “one`
  line `hundred and eighty- two days” had been substituted;`
  line `( b ) being a citizen of India, or a person of Indian origin within the meaning of Explanation to`
  line `clause ( e ) of section 115C, who, being outside India, comes on a visit to India in any previous`
  line `year, the provisions of sub-clause ( c ) shall apply in relation to that year as if for the words “sixty`
  line `days”, occurring therein, the words “one hundred and 6 [eighty- two] days” had been substituted. ]`
  line `7 [ Explanation 2. — For the purposes of this clause, in the case of an individual, being a citizen of`
  line `India and a member of the crew of a foreign bound ship leaving India, the period or periods of stay in`
  line `India shall, in respect of such voyage, be determined in the manner and subject to such conditions as`
  line `may be prescribed.]`
  line `( 2 ) A Hindu undivided family, firm or other association of persons is said to be resident in India`
  line `in any previous year in every case except where during that year the control and management of its`
  line `affairs is situated wholly outside India.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 32 of 1994, s. 4 (w.e.f. 1-4-1963).`
  line `2. Sub-clause ( b ) omitted by Act 14 of 1982, s. 3 (w.e.f. 1-4-1983).`
  line `3. Subs. by Act 36 of 1989, s. 3, for the “ Explanation ” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1990).`
  line `4. Explanation renumbered as Explanation1 thereof by Act 20 of 2015, s. 4 (w.e.f. 1-4-2015).`
  line `5. Ins. by Act 12 of 1990, s. 4 (w.e.f. 1-4-1990).`
  line `6. Subs. by Act 32 of 1994, s. 5 (w.e.f. 1-4-1995).`
  line `7. Ins. by Act 20 of 2015, s. 4 (w.e.f. 1-4-2015).`
