  line
obj_root_law_sections_738:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-738
  sectionNo (738)
  orderNo 738
  title `Page 738`
  content obj_root_law_sections_738_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_738_footnotes
  sourcePage 738
obj_root_law_sections_738_content:
  string
  line 738
  line `1 [ C. Reference to High Court`
  line `256. Statement of case to the High Court. — ( 1 ) The assessee or the 2 [Principal Commissioner or`
  line `Commissioner] may, within sixty days of the date upon which he is served with notice of 3 [an order`
  line `passed before the 1st day of October, 1998, under section 254], by application in the prescribed form,`
  line `accompanied where the application is made by the assessee by a fee of 4 [two hundred rupees], require the`
  line `Appellate Tribunal to refer to the High Court any question of law arising out of such order and, subject to`
  line `the other provisions contained in this section, the Appellate Tribunal shall, within one hundred and twenty`
  line `days of the receipt of such application, draw up a statement of the case and refer it to the High Court:`
  line `Provided that the Appellate Tribunal may, if it is satisfied that the applicant was prevented by`
  line `sufficient cause from presenting the application within the period hereinbefore specified, allow it to be`
  line `presented within a further period not exceeding thirty days.`
  line `( 2 ) If, on an application made under sub-section ( 1 ), the Appellate Tribunal refuses to state the case`
  line `on the ground that no question of law arises, the assessee or the 2 [Principal Commissioner or`
  line `Commissioner], as the case may be, may, within six months from the date on which he is served with`
  line `notice of such refusal, apply to the High Court, and the High Court may, if it is not satisfied with the`
  line `correctness of the decision of the Appellate Tribunal, require the Appellate Tribunal to state the case and`
  line `to refer it, and on receipt of any such requisition, the Appellate Tribunal shall state the case and refer it`
  line accordingly.
  line `5 [( 2A ) The High Court may admit an application after the expiry of the period of six months referred`
  line `to in sub-section ( 2 ), if it is satisfied that there was sufficient cause for not filing the same within that`
  line period.]
  line `( 3 ) Where in the exercise of its powers under sub-section ( 2 ), the Appellate Tribunal refuses to state a`
  line `case which it has been required by the assessee to state, the assessee may, within thirty days from the date`
  line `on which he receives notice of such refusal, withdraw his application, and, if he does so, the fee paid shall`
  line `be refunded.]`
  line `257. Statement of case to Supreme Court in certain cases. — If, on 6 [an application made against an`
  line `order made under section 254 before the 1st day of October, 1998, under section 256] the Appellate`
  line `Tribunal is of the opinion that, on account of a conflict in the decisions of High Courts in respect of any`
  line `particular question of law, it is expedient that a reference should be made direct to the Supreme Court, the`
  line `Appellate Tribunal may draw up a statement of the case and refer it through its President direct to the`
  line `Supreme Court.`
  line `7 [258. Power of High Court or Supreme Court to require statement to be amended. — If the High`
  line `Court or the Supreme Court is not satisfied that the statements in a case referred to it are sufficient to`
  line `enable it to determine the questions raised thereby, the Court may refer the case back to the Appellate`
  line `Tribunal for the purpose of making such additions thereto or alterations therein as it may direct in that`
  line behalf.]
  line `259. Case before High Court to be heard by not less than two judges. — ( 1 ) When any case has`
  line `been referred to the High Court under section 256, it shall be heard by a Bench of not less than two`
  line `Judges of the High Court, and shall be decided in accordance with the opinion of such judges or of the`
  line `majority, if any, of such judges.`
  line `( 2 ) Where there is no such majority, the judges shall state the point of law upon which they differ,`
  line `and the case shall then be heard upon that point only by one or more of the other judges of the High`
  line `Court, and such point shall be decided according to the opinion of the majority of the judges who have`
  line `heard the case including those who first heard it.]`
  line `1. Sub- heading “ C. Reference to High Court ” and section 256 shall stand omitted (date to be notified) by Act 49 of 2005, s.`
  line `30 and the Schedule.`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 25 of 2014, s. 4, for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -4-2013).`
  line `3. Subs. by Act 21 of 1998, s. 55, for “and order under section 254” (w.e.f. 1 -10-1998).`
  line `4. Subs. by Act 16 of 1981, s. 20, for “one hundred and twenty - five rupees” (w.e.f. 1 -6-1981).`
  line `5. Ins. by Act 14 of 2010, s. 48 (w.e.f. 1-6-2010).`
  line `6. Subs. by Act 21 of 1998, s. 56, for “an application made under Amendment section 256” (w.e.f. 1 -10-1998).`
  line `7. Section 258 shall stand omitted (date to be notified) by Act 49 of 2005, s. 30 and the Schedule.`
obj_root_law_sections_738_footnotes:
