obj_root_law_sections_833:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-833
  sectionNo (833)
  orderNo 833
  title `Page 833`
  content obj_root_law_sections_833_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_833_footnotes
  sourcePage 833
obj_root_law_sections_833_content:
  string
  line 833
  line `THE SECOND SCHEDULE`
  line `P ROCEDURE FOR RECOVERY OF TAX`
  line `1 [[ See sections 222 and 276]]`
  line `PART I`
  line __________
  line `G ENERAL P ROVISIONS`
  line `1. Definitions. — In this Schedule, unless the context otherwise requires, —`
  line `2 [( a ) “certificate”, except in rules 7, 44, 65 and sub -rule ( 2 ) of rule 66, means the certificate`
  line `drawn up by the Tax Recovery Officer under section 222 in respect of any assessee referred to in that`
  line section;]
  line `( b ) “defaulter” means the assessee mentioned in the certificate;`
  line `( c ) “execution”, in relation to a certificate, means recovery of arrears in pur suance of the`
  line certificate;
  line `( d ) “movable property” includes growing crops;`
  line `( e ) “officer” means a person authorised to make an attachment or sale under this Schedule;`
  line `( f ) “rule” means a rule contained in this Schedule; and`
  line `( g ) “share in a corporation” includ es stock, debenture-stock, debentures or bonds.`
  line `2. Issue of notice. — 3 [When a certificate has been received by the Tax Recovery Officer from the`
  line `4 [Assessing Officer]] for the recovery of arrears under this Schedule, the Tax Recovery Officer shall`
  line `cause to be served upon the defaulter a notice requiring the defaulter to pay the amount specified in the`
  line `certificate within fifteen days from the date of service of the notice and intimating that in default steps`
  line `would be taken to realise the amount under this Schedule.`
  line `3. When certificate may be executed. — No step in execution of a certificate shall be taken until the`
  line `period of fifteen days has elapsed since the date of the service of the notice required by the preceding`
  line `rule:`
  line `Provided that, if the Tax Recovery Officer is satisfied that the defaulter is likely to conceal, remove or`
  line `dispose of the whole or any part of such of his movable property as would be liable to attachment in`
  line `execution of a decree of a civil court and that the realisation of the amount of the certificate would in`
  line `consequence be delayed or obstructed, he may at any time direct, for reasons to be recorded in writing, an`
  line `attachment of the whole or any part of such property:`
  line `Provided further that if the defaulter whose property has been so attached furnishes security to the`
  line `satisfaction of the Tax Recovery Officer, such attachment shall be cancelled from the date on which such`
  line `security is accepted by the Tax Recovery Officer.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 12 4, for “ See section 222” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 124, ibid., for clause ( a ) (w.e.f. 1-4-1989).`
  line `3. Restored by Act 3 of 1989, s. 95 (1-4-1989).`
  line `4. Subs. by s. 54, ibid., for “Income - tax Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
obj_root_law_sections_833_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_834:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-834
  sectionNo (834)
  orderNo 834
  title `Page 834`
  content obj_root_law_sections_834_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_834_footnotes
  sourcePage 834
obj_root_law_sections_834_content:
  string
  line 834
  line `4. Mode of recovery. — If the amount mentioned in the notice is not paid within the time specified`
  line `therein or within such further time as the Tax Recovery Officer may grant in his discretion, the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer shall proceed to realise the amount by one or more of the following modes: —`
  line `( a ) by attachment and sale of the de faulter’s movable property;`
  line `( b ) by attachment and sale of the defaulter’s immovable property;`
  line `( c ) by arrest of the defaulter and his detention in prison;`
  line `( d ) by appointing a receiver for the management of the defaulter’s movable and immovable`
  line properties.
  line `5. Interest, costs and charges recoverable. — There shall be recoverable, in the proceedings in`
  line `execution of every certificate, —`
  line `( a ) such interest upon the amount of tax or penalty or other sum to which the certificate relates as`
  line `is payable in accordance with sub-section ( 2 ) of section 220, and`
  line `( b ) all charges incurred in respect of —`
  line `( i ) the service of notice upon the defaulter to pay the arrears, and of warrants and other`
  line `processes, and`
  line `( ii ) all other proceedings taken for realising the arrears.`
  line `6. Purchaser’ s title. — ( 1 ) Where property is sold in execution of a certificate, there shall vest in the`
  line `purchaser merely the right, title and interest of the defaulter at the time of the sale, even though the`
  line `property itself be specified.`
  line `( 2 ) Where immovable property is sold in execution of a certificate, and such sale has become`
  line `absolute, the purchaser’s right, title and interest shall be deemed to have vested in him from the time`
  line `when the property is sold, and not from the time when the sale becomes absolute.`
  line `7. Suit against purchaser not maintainable on ground of purchase being made on behalf of`
  line `plaintiff. — ( 1 ) No suit shall be maintained against any person claiming title under a purchase certified by`
  line `the Tax Recovery Officer in the manner laid down in this Schedule, on the ground that the purchase was`
  line `made on behalf of the plaintiff or on behalf of someone through whom the plaintiff claims.`
  line `( 2 ) Nothing in this section shall bar a suit to obtain a declaration that the name of any purchaser`
  line `certified as aforesaid was inserted in the certificate fraudulently or without the consent of the real`
  line `purchaser, or interfere with the right of a third person to proceed against that property, though ostensibly`
  line `sold to the certified purchaser, on the ground that it is liable to satisfy a claim of such third person against`
  line `the real owner.`
  line `1 [ 8. Disposal of proceeds of execution. — ( 1 ) Whenever assets are realised by sale or otherwise in`
  line `execution of a certificate, the proceeds shall be disposed of in the following manner, namely: —`
  line `( a ) they shall first be adjusted towards the amount due under the certificate in execution of which`
  line `the assets were realised and the costs incurred in the course of such execution;`
  line `( b ) if there remains a balance after the adjustment referred to in clause ( a ), the same shall be`
  line `utilised for satisfaction of any other amount recoverable from the assessee under this Act which may`
  line `be due on the date on which the assets were realised; and`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 124, for rule 8 (w.e.f. 1-4-1989).`
obj_root_law_sections_834_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_835:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-835
  sectionNo (835)
  orderNo 835
  title `Page 835`
  content obj_root_law_sections_835_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_835_footnotes
  sourcePage 835
obj_root_law_sections_835_content:
  string
  line 835
  line `( c ) the balance, if any, remaining after the adjustments under clauses ( a ) and ( b ) shall be paid to`
  line `the defaulter.`
  line `( 2 ) If the defaulter disputes any adjustment under clause ( b ) of sub-rule ( 1 ), the Tax Recovery Officer`
  line `shall determine the dispute.]`
  line `9. General bar to jurisdiction of civil courts, save where fraud alleged. — Except as otherwise`
  line `expressly provided in this Act, every question arising between the 1 [Tax Recovery Officer] and the`
  line `defaulter or their representatives, relating to the execution, discharge or satisfaction of a certificate 2 ***,`
  line `or relating to the confirmation or setting aside by an order under this Act of a sale held in execution of`
  line `such certificate, shall be determined, not by suit, but by order of the Tax Recovery Officer before whom`
  line `such question arises:`
  line `Provided that a suit may be brought in a civil court in respect of any such question upon the ground of`
  line fraud.
  line `10. Property exempt from attachment. — ( 1 ) All such property as is by the Code of Civil Procedure,`
  line `1908 (5 of 1908), exempted from attachment and sale in execution of a decree of a civil court shall be`
  line `exempt from attachment and sale under this Schedule.`
  line `( 2 ) The Tax Recovery Officer’s decision as to what property is so entitled to exemption shall be`
  line conclusive.
  line `11. Investigation by Tax Recovery Officer. — ( 1 ) Where any claim is preferred to, or any objection`
  line `is made to the attachment or sale of, any property in execution of a certificate, on the ground that such`
  line `property is not liable to such attachment or sale, the Tax Recovery Officer shall proceed to investigate the`
  line `claim or objection:`
  line `Provided that no such investigation shall be made where the Tax Recovery Officer considers that the`
  line `claim or objection was designedly or unnecessarily delayed.`
  line `( 2 ) Where the property to which the claim or objection applies has been advertised for sale, the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer ordering the sale may postpone it pending the investigation of the claim or objection,`
  line `upon such terms as to security or otherwise as the Tax Recovery Officer shall deem fit.`
  line `( 3 ) The claimant or objector must adduce evidence to show that —`
  line `( a ) (in the case of immovable property) at the date of the service of the notice issued under this`
  line `Schedule to pay the arrears, or`
  line `( b ) (in the case of movable property) at the date of the attachment,`
  line `he had some interest in, or was possessed of, the property in question.`
  line `( 4 ) Where, upon the said investigation, the Tax Recovery Officer is satisfied that, for the reason`
  line `stated in the claim or objection, such property was not, at the said date, in the possession of the defaulter`
  line `or of some person in trust for him or in the occupancy of a tenant or other person paying rent to him, or`
  line `that, being in the possession of the defaulter at the said date, it was so in his possession, not on his own`
  line `account or as his own property, but on account of or in trust for some other person, or partly on his own`
  line `account and partly on account of some other person, the Tax Recovery Officer shall make an order`
  line `releasing the property, wholly or to such extent as he thinks fit, from attachment or sale.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Assessing Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
  line `2. The words “duly filed under this Act” omitted by Act 4 of 1988, s. 124 (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
obj_root_law_sections_835_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_836:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-836
  sectionNo (836)
  orderNo 836
  title `Page 836`
  content obj_root_law_sections_836_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_836_footnotes
  sourcePage 836
obj_root_law_sections_836_content:
  string
  line 836
  line `( 5 ) Where the Tax Recovery Officer is satisfied that the property was, at the said date, in the`
  line `possession of the defaulter as his own property and not on account of any other person, or was in the`
  line `possession of some other person in trust for him, or in the occupancy of a tenant or other person paying`
  line `rent to him, the Tax Recovery Officer shall disallow the claim.`
  line `( 6 ) Where a claim or an objection is preferred, the party against whom an order is made may institute`
  line `a suit in a civil court to establish the right which he claims to the property in dispute; but, subject to the`
  line `result of such suit (if any), the order of the Tax Recovery Officer shall be conclusive.`
  line `12. Removal of attachment on satisfaction or cancellation of certificate. — Where —`
  line `( a ) the amount due, with costs and all charges and expenses resulting from the attachment of any`
  line `property or incurred in order to hold a sale, are paid to the Tax Recovery Officer, or`
  line `( b ) the certificate is cancelled,`
  line `the attachment shall be deemed to be withdrawn and, in the case of immovable property, the withdrawal`
  line `shall, if the defaulter so desires, be proclaimed at his expense, and a copy of the proclamation shall be`
  line `affixed in the manner provided by this Schedule for a proclamation of sale of immovable property.`
  line `13. Officer entitled to attach and sell. — The attachment and sale of movable property and the`
  line `attachment and sale of immovable property may be made by such persons as the Tax Recovery Officer`
  line `may from time to time direct.`
  line `14. Defaulting purchaser answerable for loss on resale. — Any deficiency of price which may`
  line `hap pen on a resale by reason of the purchaser’s default, and all expenses attending such resale, shall be`
  line `certified to the 1 [Tax Recovery Officer] by the officer holding the sale, and shall, at the instance of either`
  line `the Tax Recovery Officer or the defaulter, be recoverable from the defaulting purchaser under the`
  line `procedure provided by this Schedule:`
  line `Provided that no such application shall be entertained unless filed within fifteen days from the date of`
  line resale.
  line `15. Adjournment or stoppage of sale. — ( 1 ) The Tax Recovery Officer may, in his discretion,`
  line `adjourn any sale hereunder to a specified day and hour; and the officer conducting any such sale may, in`
  line `his discretion, adjourn the sale, recording his reasons for such adjournment:`
  line `Provided that, where the sale is made in, or within the precincts of, the office of the Tax Recovery`
  line `Officer, no such adjournment shall be made without the leave of the Tax Recovery Officer.`
  line `( 2 ) Where a sale of immovable property is adjourned under sub-rule ( 1 ) for a longer period than one`
  line `calendar month, a fresh proclamation of sale under this Schedule shall be made unless the defaulter`
  line `consents to waive it.`
  line `( 3 ) Every sale shall be stopped if, before the lot is knocked down, the arrears and costs (including the`
  line `costs of the sale) are tendered to the officer conducting the sale, or proof is given to his satisfaction that`
  line `the amount of such arrears and costs has been paid to the Tax Recovery Officer who ordered the sale.`
  line `16. Private alienation to be void in certain cases. — ( 1 ) Where a notice has been served on a`
  line `defaulter under rule 2, the defaulter or his representative in interest shall not be competent to mortgage,`
  line `charge, lease or otherwise deal with any property belonging to him except with the permission of the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer, nor shall any civil court issue any process against such property in execution of a`
  line `decree for the payment of money.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Assessing Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
obj_root_law_sections_836_footnotes:
  string
  line
