  string
  line 837
  line `( 2 ) Where an attachment has been made under this Schedule, any private transfer or delivery of the`
  line `property attached or of any interest therein and any payment to the defaulter of any debt, dividend or`
  line `other moneys contrary to such attachment, shall be void as against all claims enforceable under the`
  line attachment.
  line `17. Prohibition against bidding or purchase by officer. — No officer or other person having any`
  line `duty to perform in connection with any sale under this Schedule shall, either directly or indirectly, bid for,`
  line `acquire or attempt to acquire any interest in the property sold.`
  line `18. Prohibition against sale on holidays. — No sale under this Schedule shall take place on a Sunday`
  line `or other general holiday recognised by the State Government or on any day which has been notified by`
  line `the State Government to be a local holiday for the area in which the sale is to take place.`
  line `19. Assistance by police. — Any officer authorised to attach or sell any property or to arrest the`
  line `defaulter or charged with any duty to be performed under this Schedule, may apply to the officer-in-`
  line `charge of the nearest police station for such assistance as may be necessary in the discharge of his duties,`
  line `and the authority to whom such application is made shall depute a sufficient number of police officers for`
  line `furnishing such assistance.`
  line `1 [ 19A. Entrustment of certain functions by Tax Recovery Officer. — A Tax Recovery Officer may,`
  line `with the previous approval of the 2 [Joint Commissioner], entrust any of his functions as the Tax Recovery`
  line `Officer to any other officer lower than him in rank (not being lower in rank than an Inspector of`
  line `Income-tax) and such officer shall, in relation to the functions so entrusted to him, be deemed to be a Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer.]`
  line `PART II`
  line __________________
  line `A TTACHMENT AND SALE OF MOVABLE PROPERTY`
  line Attachment
  line `20. Warrant. — Except as otherwise provided in this Schedule, when any movable property is to be`
  line `attached, the officer shall be furnished by the Tax Recovery Officer (or other officer empowered by him`
  line `in that behalf) a warrant in writing and signed with his name specifying the name of the defaulter and the`
  line `amount to be realised.`
  line `21. Service of copy of warrant. — The officer shall cause a copy of the warrant to be served on the`
  line defaulter.
  line `22. Attachment. — If, after service of the copy of the warrant, the amount is not paid forthwith, the`
  line `officer shall proceed to attach the movable property of the defaulter.`
  line `23. Property in defaulter’s possession. — Where the property to be attached is movable property`
  line `(other than agricultural produce) in the possession of the defaulter, the attachment shall be made by actual`
  line `seizure, and the officer shall keep the property in his own custody or the custody of one of his`
  line `subordinates and shall be responsible for due custody thereof:`
  line `Provided that when the property seized is subject to speedy and natural decay or when the expense of`
  line `keeping it in custody is likely to exceed its value, the officer may sell it at once.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 124, for rule 19A (w.e.f. 1-4-1989).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 21 of 1998, s. 3, for “Deputy Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -10-1998).`
obj_root_law_sections_837_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_838:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-838
  sectionNo (838)
  orderNo 838
  title `Page 838`
  content obj_root_law_sections_838_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_838_footnotes
  sourcePage 838
obj_root_law_sections_838_content:
  string
  line 838
  line `24. Agricultural produce. — Where the property to be attached is agricultural produce the attachment`
  line `shall be made by affixing a copy of the warrant of attachment —`
  line `( a ) where such produce is growing crop, — on the land on which such crop has grown, or`
  line `( b ) where such produce has been cut or gathered, — on the threshing floor or place for treading out`
  line `grain or the like, or fodder-stack, on or in which it is deposited,`
  line `and another copy on the outer door or on some other conspicuous part of the house in which the defaulter`
  line `ordinarily resides, or with the leave of the Tax Recovery Officer, on the outer door or on some other`
  line `conspicuous part of the house in which he carries on business or personally works for gain, or in which he`
  line `is known to have last resided or carried on business or personally worked for gain. The produce shall,`
  line `thereupon, be deemed to have passed into the possession of the Tax Recovery Officer.`
  line `25. Provisions as to agricultural produce under attachment. — ( 1 ) Where agricultural produce is`
  line `attached, the Tax Recovery Officer shall make such arrangements for the custody, watching, tending,`
  line `cutting and gathering thereof as he may deem sufficient; 1 [and he shall have power to defray the cost of`
  line `such arrangements].`
  line `( 2 ) Subject to such conditions as may be imposed by the Tax Recovery Officer in this behalf, either in`
  line `the order of attachment or in any subsequent order, the defaulter may tend, cut, gather and store the`
  line `produce and do any other act necessary for maturing or preserving it; and, if the defaulter fails to do all or`
  line `any of such acts, any person appointed by the Tax Recovery Officer in this behalf may, subject to the like`
  line `conditions, do all or any of such acts, and the costs incurred by such person shall be recoverable from the`
  line `defaulter as if they were included in the certificate.`
  line `( 3 ) Agricultural produce attached as a growing crop shall not be deemed to have ceased to be under`
  line `attachment or to require reattachment merely because it has been severed from the soil.`
  line `( 4 ) Where an order for the attachment of a growing crop has been made at a considerable time before`
  line `the crop is likely to be fit to be cut or gathered, the Tax Recovery Officer may suspend the execution of`
  line `the order for such time as he thinks fit, and may, in his discretion, make a further order prohibiting the`
  line `removal of the crop pending the execution of the order of attachment.`
  line `( 5 ) A growing crop which from its nature does not admit of being stored shall not be attached under`
  line `this rule at any time less than twenty days before the time at which it is likely to be fit to be cut or`
  line gathered.
  line `26. Debts and shares, etc. — ( 1 ) In the case of —`
  line `( a ) a debt not secured by a negotiable instrument,`
  line `( b ) a share in a corporation, or`
  line `( c ) other movable property not in the possession of the defaulter except property deposited in, or`
  line `in the custody of, any court,`
  line `the attachment shall be made by a written order prohibiting, —`
  line `( i ) in the case of the debt — the creditor from recovering the debt and the debtor from making`
  line `payment thereof until the further order of the Tax Recovery Officer;`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “and the Assessing Officer shall bear such su m as the Tax Recovery Officer shall`
  line `require in order to defray the cost of such arrangement” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
obj_root_law_sections_838_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_839:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-839
  sectionNo (839)
  orderNo 839
  title `Page 839`
  content obj_root_law_sections_839_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_839_footnotes
  sourcePage 839
obj_root_law_sections_839_content:
  string
  line 839
  line `( ii ) in the case of the share — the person in whose name the share may be standing from`
  line `transferring the same or receiving any dividend thereon;`
  line `( iii ) in the case of the other movable property (except as aforesaid) — the person in possession of`
  line `the same from giving it over to the defaulter.`
  line `( 2 ) A copy of such order shall be affixed on some conspicuous part of the office of the Tax Recovery`
  line `Officer, and another copy shall be sent, in the case of the debt, to the debtor, in the case of the share, to`
  line `the proper officer of the corporation, and in the case of the other movable property (except as aforesaid),`
  line `to the person in possession of the same.`
  line `( 3 ) A debtor prohibited under clause ( i ) of sub-rule ( 1 ) may pay the amount of his debt to the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer, and such payment shall discharge him as effectually as payment to the party entitled to`
  line `receive the same.`
  line `27. Attachment of decree. — ( 1 ) The attachment of a decree of a civil court for the payment of money`
  line `or for sale in enforcement of a mortgage or charge shall be made by the issue to the civil court of a notice`
  line `requesting the civil court to stay the execution of the decree unless and until —`
  line `( i ) the Tax Recovery Officer cancels the notice, or`
  line `( ii ) the 1 [Tax Recovery Officer] or the defaulter applies to the court receiving such notice to`
  line `execute the decree.`
  line `( 2 ) Where a civil court receives an application under clause ( ii ) of sub-rule ( 1 ), it shall, on the`
  line `application of the 1 [Tax Recovery Officer] or the defaulter and subject to the provisions of the Code of`
  line `Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), proceed to execute the attached decree and apply the net proceeds in`
  line `satisfaction of the certificate.`
  line `( 3 ) The 1 [Tax Recovery Officer] shall be deemed to be the representative of the holder of the attached`
  line `decree, and to be entitled to execute such attached decree in any manner lawful for the holder thereof.`
  line `28. Share in movable property. — Where the property to be attached consists of the share or interest`
  line `of the defaulter in movable property belonging to him and another as co-owners, the attachment shall be`
  line `made by a notice to the defaulter prohibiting him from transferring the share or interest or charging it in`
  line `any way.`
  line `29. Salary of Government servants. — Attachment of the salary or allowances of servants of the`
  line `Government or a local authority may be made in the manner provided by rule 48 of Order 21 of the First`
  line `Schedule to the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908), and the provisions of the said rule shall, for`
  line `the purposes of this rule, apply subject to such modifications as may be necessary.`
  line `30. Attachment of negotiable instrument. — Where the property is a negotiable instrument not`
  line `deposited in a court nor in the custody of a public officer, the attachment shall be made by actual seizure,`
  line `and the instrument shall be brought before the Tax Recovery Officer and held subject to his orders.`
  line `31. Attachment of property in custody of court or public officer. — Where the property to be`
  line `attached is in the custody of any court or public officer, the attachment shall be made by a notice to such`
  line `court or officer, requesting that such property, and any interest or dividend becoming payable thereon,`
  line `may be held subject to the further orders of the Tax Recovery Officer by whom the notice is issued:`
  line `Provided that, where such property is in the custody of a court, any question of title or priority arising`
  line `between the 1 [Tax Recovery Officer] and any other person, not being the defaulter, claiming to be`
  line `interested in such property by virtue of any assignment, attachment or otherwise, shall be determined by`
  line `such court.`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Assessing Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
obj_root_law_sections_839_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_840:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-840
  sectionNo (840)
  orderNo 840
  title `Page 840`
  content obj_root_law_sections_840_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_840_footnotes
  sourcePage 840
obj_root_law_sections_840_content:
  string
  line 840
  line `32. Attachment of partnership property. — ( 1 ) Where the property to be attached consists of an`
  line `interest of the defaulter, being a partner, in the partnership property, the Tax Recovery Officer may make`
  line `an order charging the share of such partner in the partnership property and profits with payment of the`
  line `amount due under the certificate, and may, by the same or subsequent order, appoint a receiver of the`
  line `share of such partner in the profits, whether already declared or accruing and of any other money which`
  line `may become due to him in respect of the partnership, and direct accounts and inquiries and make an order`
  line `for the sale of such interest or such other order as the circumstances of the case may require.`
  line `( 2 ) The other persons shall be at liberty at any time to redeem the interest charged or, in the case of a`
  line `sale being directed, to purchase the same.`
  line `33. Inventory. — In the case of attachment of movable property by actual seizure, the officer shall,`
  line `after attachment of the property, prepare an inventory of all the property attached, specifying in it the`
  line `place where it is lodged or kept, and shall forward the same to the Tax Recovery Officer and a copy of the`
  line `inventory shall be delivered by the officer to the defaulter.`
  line `34. Attachment not to be excessive. — The attachment by seizure shall not be excessive, that is to`
  line `say, the property attached shall be as nearly as possible proportionate to the amount specified in the`
  line warrant.
  line `35. Seizure between sunrise and sunset. — Attachment by seizure shall be made after sunrise and`
  line `before sunset and not otherwise.`
  line `36. Power to break open doors, etc. — The officer may break open any inner or outer door or`
  line `window of any building and enter any building in order to seize any movable property if the officer has`
  line `reasonable grounds to believe that such building contains movable property liable to seizure under the`
  line `warrant and the officer has notified his authority and intention of breaking open if admission is not given.`
  line `He shall, however, give all reasonable opportunity to women to withdraw.`
  line Sale
  line `37. Sale. — The Tax Recovery Officer may direct that any movable property attached under this`
  line `Schedule or such portion thereof as may seem necessary to satisfy the certificate shall be sold.`
  line `38. Issue of proclamation. — When any sale of movable property is ordered by the Tax Recovery`
  line `Officer, the Tax Recovery Officer shall issue a proclamation, in the language of the district, of the`
  line `intended sale, specifying the time and place of sale and whether the sale is subject to confirmation or not.`
  line `39. Proclamation how made. — ( 1 ) Such proclamation shall be made by beat of drum or other`
  line `customary mode, —`
  line `( a ) in the case of property attached by actual seizure —`
  line `( i ) in the village in which the property was seized, or, if the property was seized in a town or`
  line `city, then, in the locality in which it was seized; and`
  line `( ii ) at such other places as the Tax Recovery Officer may direct;`
  line `( b ) in the case of property attached otherwise than by actual seizure, in such places, if any, as the`
  line `Tax Recovery Officer may direct.`
  line `( 2 ) A copy of the proclamation shall also be affixed in a conspicuous part of the office of the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer.`
  line `40. Sale after fifteen days. — Except where the property is subject to speedy and natural decay or`
  line `when the expense of keeping it in custody is likely to exceed its value, no sale of movable property under`
  line `this Schedule shall, without the consent in writing of the defaulter, take place until after the expiry of at`
  line `least fifteen days calculated from the date on which a copy of the sale proclamation was affixed in the`
  line `office of the Tax Recovery Officer.`
  line `41. Sale of agricultural produce. — ( 1 ) Where the property to be sold is agricultural produce, the sale`
  line `shall be held, —`
  line `( a ) if such produce is a growing crop — on or near the land on which such crop has grown, or`
obj_root_law_sections_840_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_841:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-841
  sectionNo (841)
  orderNo 841
  title `Page 841`
  content obj_root_law_sections_841_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_841_footnotes
  sourcePage 841
obj_root_law_sections_841_content:
  string
  line 841
  line `( b ) if such produce has been cut or gathered — at or near the threshing floor or place for treading`
  line `out grain or the like, or fodder-stack, on or in which it is deposited:`
  line `Provided that the Tax Recovery Officer may direct the sale to be held at the nearest place of public`
  line `resort, if he is of opinion that the produce is thereby likely to sell to greater advantage.`
  line `( 2 ) Where, on the produce being put up for sale, —`
  line `( a ) a fair price, in the estimation of the person holding the sale, is not offered for it, and`
  line `( b ) the owner of the produce, or a person authorised to act on his behalf, applies to have the sale`
  line `postponed till the next day or, if a market is held at the place of sale, the next market day,`
  line `the sale shall be postponed accordingly, and shall be then completed, whatever price may be offered for`
  line `the produce.`
  line `42. Special provisions relating to growing crops. — ( 1 ) Where the property to be sold is a growing`
  line `crop and the crop from its nature admits of being stored but has not yet been stored, the day of the sale`
  line `shall be so fixed as to admit of the crop being made ready for storing before the arrival of such day, and`
  line `the sale shall not be held until the crop has been cut or gathered and is ready for storing.`
  line `( 2 ) Where the crop from its nature does not admit of being stored or can be sold to a greater`
  line `advantage in an unripe stage ( e.g., as green wheat), it may be sold before it is cut and gathered, and the`
  line `purchaser shall be entitled to enter on the land, and to do all that is necessary for the purpose of tending or`
  line `cutting or gathering the crop.`
  line `43. Sale to be by auction. — The property shall be sold by public auction in one or more lots as the`
  line `officer may consider advisable, and if the amount to be realised by sale is satisfied by the sale of a portion`
  line `of the property, the sale shall be immediately stopped with respect to the remainder of the lots.`
  line `44. Sale by public auction. — ( 1 ) Where movable property is sold by public auction, the price of each`
  line `lot shall be paid at the time of sale or as soon after as the officer holding the sale directs and in default of`
  line `payment, the property shall forthwith be resold.`
  line `( 2 ) On payment of the purchase-money, the officer holding the sale shall grant a certificate specifying`
  line `the property purchased, the price paid and the name of the purchaser, and the sale shall become absolute.`
  line `( 3 ) Where the movable property to be sold is a share in goods belonging to the defaulter and a co-`
  line `owner, and two or more persons, of whom one is such co-owner, respectively bid the same sum for such`
  line `property or for any lot, the bidding shall be deemed to be the bidding of the co-owner.`
  line `45. Irregularity not to vitiate sale, but any person injured may sue. — No irregularity in publishing`
  line `or conducting the sale of movable property shall vitiate the sale, but any person sustaining substantial`
  line `injury by reason of such irregularity at the hand of any other person may institute a suit in a civil court`
  line `against him for compensation, or (if such other person is the purchaser) for the recovery of the specific`
  line `property and for compensation in default of such recovery.`
  line `46. Negotiable instruments and shares in a corporation. — Notwithstanding anything contained in`
  line `this Schedule, where the property to be sold is a negotiable instrument or a share in a corporation, the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer may, instead of directing the sale to be made by public auction, authorise the sale of`
  line `such instrument or share through a broker.`
  line `47. Order for payment of coin or currency notes to the 1 [ Assessing Officer]. — Where the property`
  line `attached is current coin or currency notes, the Tax Recovery Officer may, at any time during the`
  line `continuance of the attachment, 2 [direct that such coins or notes shall be credited to the Central`
  line `Government and the amount so credited shall be dealt with in the manner specified in rule 8].`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Income - tax Officer” (w.e.f. 1-4-1988).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 54, ibid., for “direct that such coins or notes, or a part thereof sufficient to satisfy the certificate, be paid over`
  line `to the Assessing Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
obj_root_law_sections_841_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_842:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-842
  sectionNo (842)
  orderNo 842
  title `Page 842`
  content obj_root_law_sections_842_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_842_footnotes
  sourcePage 842
obj_root_law_sections_842_content:
  string
  line 842
  line `PART III`
  line __________________
  line `A TTACHMENT AND SALE OF IMMOVABLE PROPERTY`
  line Attachment
  line `48. Attachment. — Attachment of the immovable property of the defaulter shall be made by an order`
  line `prohibiting the defaulter from transferring or charging the property in any way and prohibiting all persons`
  line `from taking any benefit under such transfer or charge.`
  line `49. Service of notice of attachment. — A copy of the order of attachment shall be served on the`
  line defaulter.
  line `50. Proclamation of attachment. — The order of attachment shall be proclaimed at some place on or`
  line `adjacent to the property attached by beat of drum or other customary mode, and a copy of the order shall`
  line `be affixed on a conspicuous part of the property and on the notice board of the office of the Tax Recovery`
  line Officer.
  line `51. Attachment to relate back from the date of service of notice. — Where any immovable property`
  line `is attached under this Schedule, the attachment shall relate back to, and take effect from, the date on`
  line `which the notice to pay the arrears, issued under this Schedule, was served upon the defaulter.`
  line Sale
  line `52. Sale and proclamation of sale. — ( 1 ) The Tax Recovery Officer may direct that any immovable`
  line `property which has been attached, or such portion thereof as may seem necessary to satisfy the certificate,`
  line `shall be sold.`
  line `( 2 ) Where any immovable property is ordered to be sold, the Tax Recovery Officer shall cause a`
  line `proclamation of the intended sale to be made in the language of the district.`
  line `53. Contents of proclamation. — A proclamation of sale of immovable property shall be drawn up`
  line `after notice to the defaulter, and shall state the time and place of sale, and shall specify, as fairly and`
  line `accurately as possible, —`
  line `( a ) the property to be sold;`
  line `( b ) the revenue, if any, assessed upon the property or any part thereof;`
  line `( c ) the amount for the recovery of which the sale is ordered; 1 ***`
  line `2 [( cc ) the reserve price, if any, below which the property may not be sold; and]`
  line `( d ) any other thing which the Tax Recovery Officer considers it material for a purchaser to know,`
  line `in order to judge the nature and value of the property.`
  line `54. Mode of making proclamation. — ( 1 ) Every proclamation for the sale of immovable property`
  line `shall be made at some place on or near such property by beat of drum or other customary mode, and a`
  line `copy of the proclamation shall be affixed on a conspicuous part of the property and also upon a`
  line `conspicuous part of the office of the Tax Recovery Officer.`
  line `1. The word “and” omitted by Act 41 of 1975, s. 81 (w.e.f. 1 -10-1975).`
  line `2. Ins. by s. 81, ibid, (w.e.f. 1-10-1975).`
obj_root_law_sections_842_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_843:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-843
  sectionNo (843)
  orderNo 843
  title `Page 843`
  content obj_root_law_sections_843_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_843_footnotes
  sourcePage 843
obj_root_law_sections_843_content:
  string
  line 843
  line `( 2 ) Where the Tax Recovery Officer so directs, such proclamation shall also be published in the`
  line `Official Gazette or in a local newspaper, or in both; and the cost of such publication shall be deemed to be`
  line `costs of the sale.`
  line `( 3 ) Where the property is divided into lots for the purpose of being sold separately, it shall not be`
  line `necessary to make a separate proclamation for each lot, unless proper notice of the sale cannot, in the`
  line `opinion of the Tax Recovery Officer, otherwise be given.`
  line `55. Time of sale. — No sale of immovable property under this Schedule shall, without the consent in`
  line `writing of the defaulter, take place until after the expiration of at least thirty days calculated from the date`
  line `on which a copy of the proclamation of sale has been affixed on the property or in the office of the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer, whichever is later.`
  line `56. Sale to be by auction. — The sale shall be by public auction to the highest bidder and shall be`
  line `subject to confirmation by the Tax Recovery Officer:`
  line `1 [Provided that no sale under this rule shall be made if the amount bid by the highest bidder is less`
  line `than the reserve price, if any, specified under clause ( cc ) of rule 53.]`
  line `57. Deposit by purchaser and resale in default. — ( 1 ) On every sale of immovable property, the`
  line `person declared to be the purchaser shall pay, immediately after such declaration, a deposit of twenty-five`
  line `per cent on the amount of his purchase money, to the officer conducting the sale; and, in default of such`
  line `deposit, the property shall forthwith be resold.`
  line `( 2 ) The full amount of purchase money payable shall be paid by the purchaser to the Tax Recovery`
  line `Officer on or before the fifteenth day from the date of the sale of the property.`
  line `58. Procedure in default of payment. — In default of payment within the period mentioned in the`
  line `preceding rule, the deposit may, if the Tax Recovery Officer thinks fit, after defraying the expenses of the`
  line `sale, be forfeited to the Government, and the property shall be resold, and the defaulting purchaser shall`
  line `forfeit all claims to the property or to any part of the sum for which it may subsequently be sold.`
  line `2 [ 59. Authority to bid. — ( 1 ) Where the sale of a property, for which a reserve price has been`
  line `specified under clause ( cc ) of rule 53, has been postponed for want of a bid of an amount not less than`
  line `such reserve price, it shall be lawful for an 3 [Assessing Officer], if so authorised by the 4 [ 5 [Principal`
  line `Chief Commissioner or Chief Commissioner] or 6 [Principal Commissioner or Commissioner]] in this`
  line `behalf, to bid for the property on behalf of the Central Government at any subsequent sale.]`
  line `7 [( 2 )] All persons bidding at the sale shall be required to declare, if they are bidding on their own`
  line `behalf or on behalf of their principals. In the latter case, they shall be required to deposit their authority,`
  line `and in default their bids shall be rejected.`
  line `1. The proviso added by Act 41 of 1975, s. 81 (w.e.f. 1-10-1975).`
  line `2. Ins. by s. 81 ibid. (w.e.f. 1-10-1975).`
  line `3. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Income - tax Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
  line `4. Subs. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 2, for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
  line `5. Subs. by Act 25 of 2014, s. 4 for “Chief Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -6-2013).`
  line `6. Subs. by s. 4, ibid., for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -6-2013).`
  line `7. The rule 59 re-numbered as sub-rule ( 2 ) thereof by Act 41 of 1975, s. 81 (w.e.f. 1-10-1975).`
obj_root_law_sections_843_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_844:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-844
  sectionNo (844)
  orderNo 844
  title `Page 844`
  content obj_root_law_sections_844_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_844_footnotes
  sourcePage 844
obj_root_law_sections_844_content:
  string
  line 844
  line `1 [( 3 ) Where the 2 [Assessing Officer] referred to in sub-rule ( 1 ) is declared to be the purchaser of the`
  line `property at any subsequent sale, nothing contained in rule 57 shall apply to the case and the amount of the`
  line `purchase price shall be adjusted towards the amount specified in the certificate.]`
  line `60. Application to set aside sale of immovable property on deposit. — ( 1 ) Where immovable`
  line `property has been sold in execution of a certificate, the defaulter, or any person whose interests are`
  line `affected by the sale, may, at any time within thirty days from the date of the sale, apply to the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer to set aside the sale, on his depositing —`
  line `( a ) 3 *** the amount specified in the proclamation of sale as that for the recovery of which the sale`
  line `was ordered, with interest thereon at the rate of 4 [one and one-fourth per cent for every month or part`
  line `of a month], calculated from the date of the proclamation of sale to the date when the deposit is made;`
  line and
  line `( b ) for payment to the purchaser, as penalty, a sum equal to five per cent of the purchase money,`
  line `but not less than one rupee.`
  line `( 2 ) Where a person makes an application under rule 61 for setting aside the sale of his immovable`
  line `property, he shall not, unless he withdraws that application, be entitled to make or prosecute an`
  line `application under this rule.`
  line `61. Application to set aside sale of immovable property on ground of non-service of notice or`
  line `irregularity. — Where immovable property has been sold in execution of a certificate, 5 [such Income-tax`
  line `Officer as may be authorised by the 6 [Principal Chief Commissioner or Chief Commissioner] or`
  line `7 [Principal Commissioner or Commissioner] in this behalf], the defaulter, or any person whose interests`
  line `are affected by the sale, may, at any time within thirty days from the date of the sale, apply to the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer to set aside the sale of the immovable property on the ground that notice was not served`
  line `on the defaulter to pay the arrears as required by this Schedule or on the ground of a material irregularity`
  line `in publishing or conducting the sale:`
  line `Provided that — ( a ) no sale shall be set aside on any such ground unless the Tax Recovery Officer is`
  line `satisfied that the applicant has sustained substantial injury by reason of the non-service or irregularity;`
  line and
  line `( b ) an application made by a defaulter under this rule shall be disallowed unless the applicant`
  line `deposits the amount recoverable from him in the execution of the certificate.`
  line `62. Setting aside sale where defaulter has no saleable interest. — At any time within thirty days of`
  line `the sale, the purchaser may apply to the Tax Recovery Officer to set aside the sale on the ground that the`
  line `defaulter had no saleable interest in the property sold.`
  line `63. Confirmation of sale. — ( 1 ) Where no application is made for setting aside the sale under the`
  line `foregoing rules or where such an application is made and disallowed by the Tax Recovery Officer, the`
  line `Tax Recovery Officer shall (if the full amount of the purchase money has been paid) make an order`
  line `confirming the sale, and, thereupon, the sale shall become absolute.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 124 (w.e.f. 1-4-1989).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Income - tax Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
  line `3. The words “for payment to the Assessing Officer” omitted by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54 (w.e.f. 1-4-1989).`
  line `4. Subs. by Act 22 of 2007, s. 81, for “fifteen per cent. per annum” (w.e.f. 1 -4-2008). Earlier it was substituted by Act 67 of`
  line `1984, s. 24 for “twelve per cent” (w.e.f. 1 -10- 1984). Earlier it was subs. by Act 16 of 1972, s. 25, for “nine per cent”`
  line `(w.e.f. 1-4- 1972). and it was subs. by Act 42 of 1970, s. 56, for “the rate of six per cent. per annum” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1971).`
  line `5. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Assessing Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1989).`
  line `6. Subs. by Act 25 of 2014, s. 4 for “Chief Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -6-2013).`
  line `7. Subs. by s. 4, ibid., for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -6-2013).`
obj_root_law_sections_844_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_845:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-845
  sectionNo (845)
  orderNo 845
  title `Page 845`
  content obj_root_law_sections_845_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_845_footnotes
  sourcePage 845
obj_root_law_sections_845_content:
  string
  line 845
  line `( 2 ) Where such application is made and allowed, and where, in the case of an application made to set`
  line `aside the sale on deposit of the amount and penalty and charges, the deposit is made within thirty days`
  line `from the date of the sale, the Tax Recovery Officer shall make an order setting aside the sale:`
  line `Provided that no order shall be made unless notice of the application has been given to the persons`
  line `affected thereby.`
  line `64. Return of purchase money in certain cases. — Where a sale of immovable property is set aside,`
  line `any money paid or deposited by the purchaser on account of the purchase, together with the penalty, if`
  line `any, deposited for payment to the purchaser, and such interest as the Tax Recovery Officer may allow,`
  line `shall be paid to the purchaser.`
  line `65. Sale certificate. — ( 1 ) Where a sale of immovable property has become absolute, the Tax`
  line `Recovery Officer shall grant a certificate specifying the property sold, and the name of the person who at`
  line `the time of sale is declared to be the purchaser.`
  line `( 2 ) Such certificate shall state the date on which the sale became absolute.`
  line `66. Postponement of sale to enable defaulter to raise amount due under certificate. — ( 1 ) Where`
  line `an order for the sale of immovable property has been made, if the defaulter can satisfy the Tax Recovery`
  line `Officer that there is reason to believe that the amount of the certificate may be raised by the mortgage or`
  line `lease or private sale of such property, or some part thereof, or of any other immovable property of the`
  line `defaulter, the Tax Recovery Officer may, on his application, postpone the sale of the property comprised`
  line `in the order for sale, on such terms, and for such period as he thinks proper, to enable him to raise the`
  line amount.
  line `( 2 ) In such case, the Tax Recovery Officer shall grant a certificate to the defaulter, authorising him,`
  line `within a period to be mentioned therein, and notwithstanding anything contained in this Schedule, to`
  line `make the proposed mortgage, lease or sale:`
  line `Provided that all moneys payable under such mortgage, lease or sale shall be paid, not to the`
  line `defaulter, but to the Tax Recovery Officer:`
  line `Provided also that no mortgage, lease or sale under this rule shall become absolute until it has been`
  line `confirmed by the Tax Recovery Officer.`
  line `67. Fresh proclamation before re-sale. — Every re-sale of immovable property, in default of`
  line `payment of the purchase money within the period allowed for such payment, shall be made after the issue`
  line `of a fresh proclamation in the manner and for the period hereinbefore provided for the sale.`
  line `68. Bid of co-sharer to have preference. — Where the property sold is a share of undivided`
  line `immovable property, and two or more persons, of whom one is a co-sharer, respectively bid the same sum`
  line `for such property or for any lot, the bid shall be deemed to be the bid of the co-sharer.`
  line `1 [ 68A. Acceptance of property in satisfaction of amount due from the defaulter. — ( 1 ) Without`
  line `prejudice to the provisions contained in this Part, an 2 [Assessing Officer], duly authorised by the`
  line `3 [ 4 [Principal Chief Commissioner or Chief Commissioner] or 5 [Principal Commissioner or`
  line `Commissioner]] in this behalf, may accept in satisfaction of the whole or any part of the amount due from`
  line `he defaulter the property, the sale of which has been postponed for the reason mentioned in sub-rule ( 1 ) of`
  line `rule 59, at such price as may be agreed upon between the 2 [Assessing Officer] and the defaulter.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 41 of 1975, s. 81 (w.e.f. 1-10-1975).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Income - tax Officer” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
  line `3. Subs. by A ct 4 of 1988, s. 2, for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
  line `4. Subs. by Act 25 of 2014, s. 4 for “Chief Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -6-2013).`
  line `5. Subs. by s. 4, ibid., for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -6-2013).`
obj_root_law_sections_845_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_846:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-846
  sectionNo (846)
  orderNo 846
  title `Page 846`
  content obj_root_law_sections_846_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_846_footnotes
  sourcePage 846
obj_root_law_sections_846_content:
  string
  line 846
  line `( 2 ) Where any property is accepted under sub-rule ( 1 ), the defaulter shall deliver possession of such`
  line `property to the 1 [Assessing Officer] and on the date the possession of the property is delivered to the`
  line `1 [Assessing Officer], the property shall vest in the Central Government and the Central Government shall,`
  line `where necessary, intimate the concerned Registering Officer appointed under the Registration Act, 1908`
  line `(16 of 1908), accordingly.`
  line `( 3 ) Where the price of the property agreed upon under sub-rule ( 1 ) exceeds the amount due from the`
  line `defaulter, such excess shall be paid by the 1 [Assessing Officer] to the defaulter within a period of three`
  line `months from the date of delivery of possession of the property and where the 1 [Assessing Officer] fails to`
  line `pay such excess within the period aforesaid, the Central Government shall, for the period commencing on`
  line `the expiry of such period and ending with the date of payment of the amount remaining unpaid, pay`
  line `simple interest at 2 [one-half per cent. for every month or part of a month] to the defaulter on such`
  line amount.]
  line `3 [ 68B. Time limit for sale of attached immovable property. — ( 1 ) No sale of immovable property`
  line `shall be made under this Part after the expiry of three years from the end of the financial year in which the`
  line `order giving rise to a demand of any tax, interest, fine, penalty or any other sum, for the recovery of`
  line `which the immovable property has been attached, has become conclusive under the provisions of`
  line `section 245-I or, as the case may be, final in terms of the provisions of Chapter XX:`
  line `Provided that where the immovable property is required to be re-sold due to the amount of highest bid`
  line `being less than the reserve price or under the circumstances mentioned in rule 57 or rule 58 or where the`
  line `sale is set aside under rule 61, the aforesaid period of limitation for the sale of the immovable property`
  line `shall stand extended by one year.`
  line `( 2 ) In computing the period of limitation under sub-rule ( 1 ), the period —`
  line `( i ) during which the levy of the aforesaid tax, interest, fine, penalty or any other sum is stayed by`
  line `an order or injunction of any court; or`
  line `( ii ) during which the proceedings of attachment or sale of the immovable property are stayed by`
  line `an order or injunction of any court; or`
  line `( iii ) commencing from the date of the presentation of any appeal against the order passed by the`
  line `Tax Recovery Officer under this Schedule and ending on the day the appeal is decided,`
  line `shall be excluded:`
  line `Provided that where immediately after the exclusion of the aforesaid period, the period of limitation`
  line `for the sale of the immovable property is less than 180 days, such remaining period shall be extended to`
  line `180 days and the aforesaid period of limitation shall be deemed to be extended accordingly.`
  line `( 3 ) Where any immovable property has been attached under this Part before the 1st day of June, 1992,`
  line `and the order giving rise to a demand of any tax, interest, fine, penalty or any other sum, for the recovery`
  line `of which the immovable property has been attached, has also become conclusive or final before the said`
  line `date, that date shall be deemed to be the date on which the said order has become conclusive or, as the`
  line `case may be, final.`
  line `( 4 ) Where the sale of immovable property is not made in accordance with the provisions of`
  line `sub-rule ( 1 ), the attachment order in relation to the said property shall be deemed to have been vacated on`
  line `the expiry of the time of limitation specified under this rule.]`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 54, for “Income - tax Officer” (w.e.f. 1-4-1988).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 22 of 2007, s. 81, for “six per cent. per annum” (w.e.f. 1 -4-2008). Earlier it was substituted`
  line `by Act 54 of 2003, s. 21, for “eight per cent” (w.e.f. 8 -9-2003). Earlier it was substituted by Act 20 of 2002, s. 109`
  line `(w.e.f. 1-6-2002). and it was substituted by Act 14 of 2001, s. 95, (w.e.f. 1-6-2001).`
  line `3. Ins. by Act 18 of 1992, s. 87 (w.e.f. 1-6-1992).`
obj_root_law_sections_846_footnotes:
